Interview Questions

Q1. What is Collection Framework? What are the advantages of the Collection Framework in Java?
-->


Collection Framework

The Java Collection Framework (JCF) is a set of interfaces, classes, and algorithms provided by the java.util package to store, manage, and manipulate groups of objects efficiently.

Examples: ArrayList, LinkedList, HashSet, TreeSet, HashMap, etc.

Advantages
Reusable Data Structures – Ready-made classes like ArrayList, HashSet, and HashMap.
Dynamic Size – Collections can grow or shrink automatically.
Improved Performance – Optimized implementations for searching, sorting, and storing data.
Code Reusability – No need to implement data structures from scratch.
Type Safety – Generics ensure only specific types of objects are stored.
Standard API – Provides a common way to access and manipulate data.
Utility Methods – Collections class provides sorting, searching, reversing, shuffling, etc.
Easy Data Manipulation – Supports insertion, deletion, iteration, and modification.



Q2. Describe the Collection hierarchy in Java.
-->The Java Collection Framework hierarchy is as follows:
                 Iterable
                     |
               Collection (Interface)
          ___________|____________
         |           |            |
       List         Set        Queue
        |            |            |
  ArrayList      HashSet     PriorityQueue
  LinkedList     LinkedHashSet
  Vector         TreeSet
  Stack

                Map (Separate Interface)
                     |
        ______________________________
       |              |               |
    HashMap     LinkedHashMap      TreeMap
                                   Hashtable


Hierarchy Explanation

Iterable → Root interface for iteration using Iterator.
Collection → Parent interface of List, Set, and Queue.
List → Ordered collection, allows duplicates.
Set → Does not allow duplicate elements.
Queue → Stores elements for processing, usually in FIFO order.
Map → Stores key-value pairs. It is not part of the Collection interface hierarchy.





Q3. List down the primary interfaces provided by the Java Collections Framework.
-->The primary interfaces are:

Iterable – Root interface for iteration.
Collection – Root interface for all collections.
List – Ordered collection with duplicates allowed.
Set – Collection of unique elements.
SortedSet – Set whose elements are sorted.
NavigableSet – Extends SortedSet with navigation methods.
Queue – FIFO data structure.
Deque – Double-ended queue.
Map – Stores key-value pairs.
SortedMap – Keys are maintained in sorted order.
NavigableMap – Extends SortedMap with navigation methods.



Q4. Why doesn't the Collection interface extend the Cloneable and Serializable interfaces?
-->The Collection interface does not extend Cloneable and Serializable because:

Not all collections need cloning or serialization.
Cloning behavior differs among implementations, so a common implementation is not possible.
Serialization is optional because some collections may contain non-serializable objects.
These are implementation-specific features, so classes like ArrayList, HashSet, and HashMap implement them individually when required.

Example:

ArrayList implements both Cloneable and Serializable.
The Collection interface itself does not.




Q5. What is Generic Collection?
-->A Generic Collection is a collection that specifies the type of objects it can store using Generics (<T>).

Syntax:

Collection<Type> collectionName = new CollectionImplementation<>();

Example:

import java.util.*;

public class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<String> names = new ArrayList<>();

        names.add("Karthik");
        names.add("Rahul");

        // names.add(100); // Compile-time Error

        for (String name : names) {
            System.out.println(name);
        }
    }
}

Advantages

Type safety
No explicit type casting
Compile-time error checking
Cleaner and more readable code




Q6. What is the difference between Collection and Array?
-->
| **Collection**                                            | **Array**                             |
| --------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------- |
| Dynamic size                                              | Fixed size                            |
| Stores objects only (Generics support)                    | Can store primitive types and objects |
| Located in `java.util` package                            | Built into Java language              |
| Many built-in methods (`add()`, `remove()`, `contains()`) | Limited operations                    |
| Memory allocated dynamically                              | Memory allocated at creation          |
| Can use Generics                                          | Cannot use Generics                   |
| Slower than arrays in some cases                          | Faster due to direct memory access    |
| Example: `ArrayList`, `HashSet`                           | Example: `int[]`, `String[]`          |



Example (Array):

int[] arr = {10, 20, 30};

Example (Collection):

List<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();
list.add(10);
list.add(20);
list.add(30);
Interview Tip

A common interview question is:

Why use Collections instead of Arrays?

Answer: Collections are preferred because they are dynamic, provide built-in methods, support Generics, and offer better flexibility,
whereas arrays have a fixed size and fewer utility methods.
